Document: Game Embedding
Path: godot/tutorials/editor/game_embedding.rst
Summary: Describes how to pause and resume the game in the editor to interact with running game elements.
Pause (F9)
Pauses/resumes the game. When paused, the game will stop processing physics and idle frames, but it will still render and process input. This allows you to select nodes in the scene and inspect their properties in the editor inspector while the game is running.
---CHUNK---
Document: Game Embedding Tutorial
Path: godot/tutorials/editor/game_embedding.rst
Summary: Explains the frame advance feature in the Godot editor for debugging.
Frame advance (F10) is available only when the game is paused. It advances the game by one frame, allowing inspection of the game state at a specific moment. This is useful for diagnosing short-lived interactions, such as collisions, that are difficult to observe when the game runs at full speed.
---CHUNK---
Document: Game Embedding Tutorial
Path: godot/tutorials/editor/game_embedding.rst
Summary: This section explains the game speed adjustment feature in the Godot editor's game bar and its interaction with physics.
This option is a menu that can adjust the game speed. If the game sets Engine.time_scale at runtime, it will be multiplied by the value set here.

This can be used to view interactions in slow motion, or speed up the game significantly to test mechanics that normally take a long time to occur.

The reset button to the right of the dropdown resets the game speed to normal (1.0×).

Tip: When adjusting the game speed using this mechanism, the physics tick rate (determined by the ProjectSettings.physics/common/physics_ticks_per_second project setting) is automatically multiplied by the game speed. This allows the game logic to run at a different speed without affecting the physics simulation. For example:

- If you set the game speed to 0.5, the physics tick rate is halved.
- If you set the game speed to 4.0, the physics tick rate is quadrupled.

The ProjectSettings.physics/common/max_physics_steps_per_frame is also increased to match the new physics tick rate, but it will not decrease below the default value when running in slow motion.
---CHUNK---
Document: Game Embedding Tutorial
Path: godot/tutorials/editor/game_embedding.rst
Summary: This section explains the different interaction modes available when debugging an embedded game in the Godot editor.

Interaction mode controls the behavior when clicking or pressing keys while the embedded game window has focus.

*   **Input** (default): Allows game input as usual.
*   **2D:** Disables game input and allows selecting Node2Ds, Controls, and manipulating the 2D camera.
*   **3D:** Disables game input and allows selecting Node3Ds and manipulating the 3D camera.

Nodes selected in 2D and 3D modes can be inspected in the editor's inspector, similar to selecting nodes in the editor. This enables inspecting and modifying properties of nodes in the running game.

Warning: Changes made to the running game this way are not preserved when the game is stopped. To make changes that are preserved after stopping the game, select the nodes in the editor's Local scene tree and modify them from there while the game is running. Ensure Debug > Synchronize Scene Changes is enabled when doing this.
---CHUNK---
